(November 1989)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.the-compass.com/essays/essay_the_environmental_heresy_part_1.htm">www.the-compass.com/essays/essay_the_environmental_heresy_part_1.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
James Bowman, writing August 9, 1989, in the Spectator (the real one, edited in London these past 161 years), traced the Environmental &quot;Movement&quot; to Rousseau. RousseauÅfs real originality, wrote Bowman, was in &quot;dethroning reason.&quot; He argued that our inward natures, consisting of intuition and feeling, were shared with all other living creatures. Hence, the belief that man was made in the image of God was incomprehensible.<br>
<br>
That, said Bowman, planted the seed for a political argument to end human privilege over nature as surely as it led, more immediately, to the political arguments that ended aristocratic privilege in society.<br>
<br>
That is a perceptive observation, and Bowman interestingly traced it with references to the Romantics and their great love of scenery, to FreudÅfs complaints about the &quot;repressions&quot; of civilization and to the Nazi addictions to animals and vegetarianism.<br>
<br>
His conclusion is that &quot;Rousseau forged the revolutionary creed from which are descended both socialism and environmentalism in their militant and distinctively political forms. If now the last of the socialist line appears to be moribund in its Eastern fastnesses, the title of mankindÅfs revolutionary faith will pass to the more vigorous collateral line. And God help us all when the heir begins to take the estate in hand.&quot;<br>
<br>
Since, in other words, the socialist message has done as much mischief as possible and is now losing momentum, environmentalism, its first cousin, can continue the effort to place all the world under the authority of a new elite.<br>
<br>
Stating the situation in political-intellectual terms is, however, not enough. The socialist analogy, though accurate, is incomplete. Dr. Edwin Vieira, Jr., saw more deeply when he termed the unending stream of &quot;nature&quot; films on PBS propaganda for Animism.<br>
<br>
Animism is, of course, the most primitive of religions, the belief that all forms of life &amp;#8212; poisonous snakes, tsetse flies, electric eels, sharks, rabbits and hyenas, vultures and vampire bats &amp;#8212; are equally sacred. The PBS films subtly exclude people from areas where animals, insects, reptiles, and birds abound; they radiate agreement with D.H. LawrenceÅfs theme that &quot;we might spare a million or two of humans, and never miss them, so much as a single mountain lion.&quot;<br>
<br>
None of this is, today, remote. The old Marxist-socialist nonsense has barely dwindled, with starving Russians, Poles, Rumanians, Chinese, Cubans, and Cambodians as living relics of folly. We are awash in protests against factories, mines, mills, energy fuels, and the other accomplishments of modern civilization.<br>
<br>
As long as such protests were limited to obvious abuses, they served a useful purpose; as in socialist arguments against abuses in the workplace, they were nearly unanswerable correctives. As long as it was only the Greens of Western Germany who claimed to be the sole environmental guardians, we could overlook their Kremlin subsidy and shrug our shoulders.<br>
<br>
But environmental arguments now blanket our nation and, obviously, Europe. The movement has seduced our courts and Congress, our White House and our bureaucracy, our media and our churches, our marketplaces and people. This movement deserves serious attention &amp;#8212; and resistance.<br>
<br>
That is not easy, because environmentalism, like socialism, claims to occupy unanswerable ethical grounds. As Bowman said, the idea that the more fortunate should assist the less fortunate is a sound argument. Similarly, those who foul the atmosphere should clean it up.<br>
<br>
Just as socialism carried an echo of Christian compassion, so environmentalism reeks with self-conscious virtue: with concern for the health of children and adults alike, with kinship to all the creatures, plants and elements of the earth. The problem is that these claims deny qualification. They are flaunted as absolutes, not practicalities.<br>
<br>
&quot;Any social order which selects a single good principle,&quot; wrote Bowman, &quot;whether that of equality or tidiness, and ruthlessly makes all other good principles subordinate to it, results in a tyranny.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tyranny is a condition Americans pride themselves in detesting. But in reality, we are closer to such a condition than we dare openly admit. Who among us does not fear our government?<br>
<br>
We have moved toward that dread situation unwittingly &amp;#8212; almost like sleepwalkers. And one of the ways we have been subtly coaxed toward self-destruction has been by the argument that any qualifications we voice toward environmentalism, or involving welfarism, or the race industry, or any other great contemporary societal situation, is regarded as ipso facto proof that we are in favor of unlimited spoliations of the air, against any and all forms of welfare, are racists or anti-poor people.<br>
<br>
This fashion has grown so immense that all issues now have a single official, media-mandated position. Dissenters are shouted down, hounded off the stage, subjected to personal attacks, and thereafter denied platforms.<br>
<br>
This has become true of environmentalism. Housewives rise in public to berate engineers, and carry the crowd &amp;#8212; because the reports of engineers are held to be tainted by association with an industrial enterprise, while the virtue (and wisdom) of neighborhood viragos is beyond question.<br>
<br>
As public hearings, debates, media articles and books now make clear, the socialist version of industry as exploitation of the poor has now shifted to accusation that heavy industry is a series of malignant activities designed to poison the earth and to blight the lives of the people, for profit.<br>
<br>
Oil, coal, wood, and nuclear power are all evil. Only air, sunlight, water and wind should be harnessed &amp;#8212; and water only after horrendous battles. The petroleum industry should cease to function in this land; automobiles are endangering our lives and should be curtailed; so should jet planes, chemical plants, dump sites, and mines.<br>
<br>
The movement now serves as an umbrella for peaceniks, socialists, educators, theatrical groups, musicians, social dropouts, the &quot;beautiful people,&quot; and the dispossessed alike.<br>
<br>
Its ranks include the clergy and the unchurched, the ignorant and the highly educated, the skilled and the unskilled.<br>
<br>
What unites all these people? They drive automobiles to meetings where speakers use electrically-powered microphones to denounce the energy industry. They use gasoline produced by refineries they denounce; they leave the meeting to return home where they turn on the heat or the air conditioning, or switch on the TV and the lights, and settle back in a virtuous glow at having struck a shared blow for what? &amp;#8212; for their uneasy consciences, for painless virtue, for the &quot;courage&quot; to stand amid a friendly crowd, for saying what everyone around them is saying, for the similitude of a vanished community interest, for the hope of being included in a video sweep on the evening news.<br>
<br>
Some, of course, have more serious motives. They are attorneys available for anyone to use in a lawsuit against a nearby factory, a refinery, a dump operation, a power plant, a chemical manufactory. There are newspaper and radio/TV stations anxious to hear complaints, courts to welcome charges, and judges and juries anxious to punish corporate evildoers.<br>
<br>
This is, after all, a society at war with itself, a people educated to despise its own history, to deny its majority religion, a lost people whose traditions are treated with contempt by its elite, a people in search of virtue at a time when none appears at the top &amp;#8212; a people in search of a faith, who are now confronted with an old heresy in a new form.<br>
